  // Israel
  "tel-aviv": "Tel Aviv leads Israel's EV adoption with one of the highest concentrations of charging infrastructure in the Middle East. The city's dense urban core, tech-savvy population, and municipal investment in green transport have made charging stations a common sight in shopping centers, parking garages, and along major boulevards. Drivers in Tel Aviv benefit from relatively short distances between chargers, particularly around the Azrieli complex, the beachfront promenade, and the northern neighborhoods of Ramat Aviv.",

  "jerusalem": "Jerusalem's EV charging network has expanded significantly in recent years, reflecting the city's commitment to reducing emissions in one of the world's most visited cities. Charging points are concentrated around major commercial zones, government buildings, and tourist destinations. Drivers visiting the Old City area, Mamilla Mall, or the Hebrew University campus will find accessible charging options nearby, though coverage in some residential neighborhoods remains uneven.",

  "haifa": "Haifa, Israel's northern port city and home to a major technology corridor, has developed a solid EV charging infrastructure along the Carmel ridge and in the Hadar and downtown areas. The city's hilly terrain makes efficient route planning important for EV drivers, and chargers are strategically placed near shopping centers and public parking facilities. Haifa's Matam technology park — one of Israel's largest tech hubs — hosts several workplace charging stations.",

  "rishon-lezion": "Rishon LeZion, one of Israel's largest cities, has invested in expanding its EV infrastructure as part of broader urban development plans. Charging stations are available at major commercial centers including the Big Fashion mall and city-operated parking facilities. The city's flat terrain and well-connected road network make it a convenient base for EV drivers traveling through the central region.",

  "petah-tikva": "Petah Tikva, located in the heart of the Dan metropolitan area, offers EV drivers access to charging stations distributed across its commercial and business districts. The city is home to several large employers with workplace charging programs, and public chargers are available near the main shopping areas and municipal parking lots.",

  "beer-sheva": "Be'er Sheva, the capital of Israel's Negev desert region, serves as a key charging hub for drivers traveling through southern Israel. The city's EV infrastructure is concentrated around Ben-Gurion University, the Grand Canyon shopping mall, and the renovated city center. For drivers planning long-distance trips through the Negev, Be'er Sheva is an essential charging stop.",

  "netanya": "Netanya, a coastal city north of Tel Aviv, has developed EV charging infrastructure that serves both residents and tourists visiting its popular beaches. Charging stations are available near the city center, along the beachfront area, and at major commercial locations. The city's position on the coastal highway makes it a practical stop for northbound EV drivers.",

  "ashdod": "Ashdod, one of Israel's major port cities, has gradually expanded its EV charging network in line with the region's growing adoption of electric vehicles. Charging points are available near the city's commercial centers and in select parking facilities. Drivers transiting between Tel Aviv and the southern regions will find Ashdod a useful stop.",

  "eilat": "Eilat, Israel's southernmost city and a popular resort destination on the Red Sea, presents unique considerations for EV drivers given its remote location at the end of a long desert highway. Charging infrastructure in Eilat is available at hotels and commercial centers, but drivers should plan carefully for the journey south, as the Negev highway has limited charging options between Be'er Sheva and Eilat.",

  // California
  "los-angeles": "Los Angeles is one of the most EV-friendly cities in the United States, with California's aggressive zero-emission vehicle mandates driving widespread charging infrastructure across the metro area. From Santa Monica to Downtown LA and the San Fernando Valley, charging stations are embedded in parking structures, retail centers, and along major corridors. The city's sprawling geography means that planning charging stops is part of everyday driving for LA's large EV community.",

  "san-francisco": "San Francisco consistently ranks among the top US cities for EV infrastructure density, supported by California's clean energy policies and a tech-forward population that adopted electric vehicles early. Charging stations are concentrated in the Financial District, SoMa, the Mission, and along Caltrain corridors. The city's compact geography and high parking costs have made destination charging at shopping centers and garages particularly popular.",

